\begin_layout Section
Empirical model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Atolia model predicts sector-specific changes in capital accumulation.
 Ideally, we would like to directly measure these effects.
 However, there is no extant cross-country data on capital stock by sectors.
 Atolia nevertheless predicts an overall change in the aggregate capital
 stock of the country, so we can still hope to test the model with aggregate
 capital data.
 The theoretical model suggests two relationships, the first of which can
 be modeled by the following equation: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\dfrac{K_{it}}{K_{it-1}}=\alpha+\beta_{\tau K}\tau_{it}^{K}+\beta_{\tau C}\tau_{it}^{C}+\beta_{\tau K\times C}\tau_{it}^{K}\times\tau_{it}^{C}+u_{it}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $K_{it}$
\end_inset

 is the capital stock per capita in country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{it}^{K}$
\end_inset

is the tariff on capital goods, and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{it}^{C}$
\end_inset

is the tariff on consumption goods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This capital-tariff equation captures Atolia's predictions of the effect
 of trade liberalization on the rate of capital accumulation.
 Since a cut only to tariffs on consumption goods will cause the capital-intensi
ve import-competing sector to contract, with no corresponding rise in capital
 in the export-oriented sector, we expect 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{\tau C}>0$
\end_inset

.
 When both capital and consumption tariffs are cut, the export-oriented
 sector accumulates capital faster than the import-competing sector decumulates
 it, so we expect 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{\tau K\times C}<0$
\end_inset

.
 This cross term is interpreted as an interaction effect: the additional
 effect when a country is a liberalizer in both capital and consumption
 goods trade.
 Atolia is silent on what would happen if only capital tariffs were cut,
 but the economy-wide lower price in capital should increase the incentive
 to accumulate capital, so we predict that 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{\tau K}<0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second equation that the Atolia model suggests is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\dfrac{w_{H\, it}}{w_{L\, it}}=\alpha'+\beta_{K}\ln K_{it}+v_{it}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\dfrac{w_{H\, it}}{w_{L\, it}}$
\end_inset

 is the ratio of high-skilled wage to low-skilled wage and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $K_{it}$
\end_inset

 is the capital stock per capita.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under the Atolia assumption of complementarity between high skill labor
 and capital, a higher stock of capital should raise the wage premium for
 high-skill workers.
 Hence the prediction of the theory is 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{K}>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since capital appears on the left side of the first equation and the right
 side of the second equation, the structure of the two equations above may
 suggest a two-stage least squares approach.
 However, proceeding in that way would require us to assume that trade liberaliz
ation only affects the wage premium through its affect on capital accumulation,
 which we are not prepared to claim.
 Moreover, the capital-tariff equation deals with the 
\shape italic
growth
\shape default
 of capital, while the wage-capital equation involves the 
\shape italic
level
\shape default
 of capital, ruling out a two-stage least squares strategy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will use first difference to condition on country-specific effects.
 Our identification strategy is thus difference-in-differences, where the
 treatment is continuous (tariff and capital stock levels) rather than discrete.
 We need the parallel trend assumption for identification.
 On the capital-tariff relationship, this requires countries with a high
 tariff would have had the same change in the rate of capital accumulation
 as those with a low tariff, absent the actual change in trade policy.
 Similarly, in the wage-capital relationship we need low-capital countries
 to have had the same change in wage premium as the high-capital countries,
 absent the actual rise in capital.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our data on disaggregated tariffs limits us to estimating the above equations
 with just two periods: roughly the late 1980's to the early 2000's.
 This time frame is well within the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

short run
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 period of Atolia, since his numerical simulations indicate worsening inequality
 for thirty years or more.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Estimation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since we are estimating two equations with the same sample, a seemingly
 unrelated regressions approach permits us to obtain more efficient estimates
 of the parameters.
 We have a small number of observations, so any increase in statistical
 power is welcome.
 In practice, the residuals of the two regressions are nearly uncorrelated,
 so there is little advantage to using seemingly unrelated regressions compared
 with estimating each equation individually.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Endogeneity is a concern in the two equations.
 To handle this problem, we can use three-stage least squares.
 This involves simply instrumenting for endogenous variables in each equation
 individually and then using the seemingly unrelated regressions technique
 to make use of the correlated residuals of the two equations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Endogeneity in the capital-tariff equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To deal with possible endogeneity problem in this equation, we will follow
 the instrumental variable technique done in Estavadeordal & Taylor (2013).
 The author study the effect of trade liberalization on economic growth
 using two different instruments: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Average\, Tariffs_{1985}\times GATT\, membership_{1975}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Average\, Tariffs_{1985}\times Great\, Depression\, Intensity
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $Great\, Depression\, Intensity=GDP_{1935}/GDP_{1929}.$
\end_inset

 They believe that these instruments indicate both ability and willingness
 of countries to engage in trade liberalization movement in the mid 1980s
 to 1990s.
 First part of both instruments is average tariffs in 1985.
 They argue that if a country has high tariff in 1985, it would have ability
 to have a big tariff cut in the following period.
 The second component of the first instrument is a binary variable indicating
 GATT membership in 1975.
 If a country was a member of GATT, then it would be more likely to later
 join trade liberalization movement.
 For the second instrument, the second component is how much a country suffered
 from the Great Depression.
 The authors argue that this determines policy makers' openness to trade.
 They find that these provide strong instruments for tariffs variables.
 To be able to use these instruments we have to make sure exclusion restrictions
 is valid.
 In other words, there is no direct relationship between the two instruments
 and our dependent variable 
\emph on
capital accumulation.
 
\emph default
For 
\emph on
Great Depression Intensity, 
\emph default
we believe that factors affecting GDP in the 1930s are not the same factors
 affecting capital accumulation in the 1980-90s.
 For 
\emph on
GATT membership, 
\emph default
we also believe that the decision to enter GATT in 1975 should not have
 any impact on 1980s to 1990s capital accumulation.
 Therefore, exclusion restriction should be valid.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Endogeneity in the wage-capital equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We should be concerned about simultaneous causation in equation #<>.
 Modeling only one side of the supply-demand relationship is a well-known
 pitfall in econometrics.
 However, the relationship between capital stock and the wage premium is
 indirect: it operates through the complementarity of capital and high-skilled
 labor.
 Therefore, it is not appropriate to model the relationship as a full supply-dem
and simultaneous equation system.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will still take an instrumental variable approach.
 A straightforward instrument for the level of capital stock is 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, the price of capital accumulation.
 In a closed economy, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is determined endogenously; firms' solutions to their profit maximization
 problems should ensure that 
\begin_inset Formula $r=\nicefrac{\partial F}{\partial K}$
\end_inset

