\begin_layout Section
Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In light of our empirical test, we cannot reject the Atolia theory.
 The precision of our estimates suffers badly from a small sample size.
 As a result, we cannot be sure of the sign of the effect of tariff levels
 on capital accumulation, or even if it is nonzero.
 On the other hand, the positive effect of capital accumulation on the wage
 premium among developing countries offers limited support for the theory.
 In some sense, this effect is the less important part of the theory since
 it could, arguably, be unrelated to trade.
 The estimated elasticity of the wage premium with respect to the level
 of capital stock in developing countries is 0.3.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our estimation strategy suffers from a few weaknesses.
 Our inability to eliminate possible endogeneity in the wage-capital equation
 softens confidence in our results somewhat.
 We were not able to obtain sector-specific estimates of capital stock,
 which prevents us from having a sharp identification of the Atolia model.
 Finally, in recent years economists have challenged the robustness of cross-cou
ntry regressions (Durlauf 2009
